  "text": "# Kafka Consumer API Migration Analysis\n\n## Overview\n\nThe analysis examined the migration from the legacy Kafka ConsumerConnector API to the modern KafkaConsumer API in Apache Kafka. The current codebase (apache/kafka at commit 0753c489) implements the new KafkaConsumer API as the primary consumer interface.\n\n## Key Implementation Files\n\n### New KafkaConsumer API (New Implementation)\n\n**Main API Classes:**\n- `KafkaConsumer` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/KafkaConsumer.java): The primary public consumer API implementing the Consumer interface. Provides poll-based consumption model with subscription or manual assignment.\n- `Consumer` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/Consumer.java): Interface defining the consumer contract with methods for subscription, polling, and offset management.\n\n### Internal Implementation Architecture\n\nThe current KafkaConsumer uses a delegated architecture with two internal implementations:\n\n1. **AsyncKafkaConsumer** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/AsyncKafkaConsumer.java): Implements the new consumer group protocol (KIP-848) with event-driven architecture. Both the class and methods like `close(Duration)` are marked as @Deprecated, indicating transition to newer approaches.\n\n2. **ClassicKafkaConsumer** (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ClassicKafkaConsumer.java): Implements the legacy consumer group protocol. Also marked as @Deprecated, similar to AsyncKafkaConsumer.\n\n**Delegation Logic:**\n- `ConsumerDelegateCreator` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ConsumerDelegateCreator.java): Factory that selects between AsyncKafkaConsumer and ClassicKafkaConsumer based on the group protocol configuration. If `group.protocol` is set to \"consumer\", it uses AsyncKafkaConsumer; otherwise ClassicKafkaConsumer.\n- `ConsumerDelegate` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/ConsumerDelegate.java): Interface that both implementations implement to provide a common abstraction.\n\n## Offset Management Key Differences\n\n### 1. **Offset Representation**\n\n**New API (KafkaConsumer):**\n- Uses `OffsetAndMetadata` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/OffsetAndMetadata.java) to represent offsets\n- Includes:\n  - `offset`: The committed offset value\n  - `metadata`: Optional application metadata (String)\n  - `leaderEpoch`: Optional leader epoch for log truncation detection\n- Constructor: `OffsetAndMetadata(long offset, Optional<Integer> leaderEpoch, String metadata)`\n\n### 2. **Position Tracking**\n\n**New API:**\n- Uses `SubscriptionState` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/SubscriptionState.java) for tracking:\n  - Assigned partitions (either via subscription or manual assignment)\n  - Current position: The offset of the next record to be returned\n  - Committed position: The last securely stored offset\n  - Pause state for individual partitions\n\n### 3. **Offset Commit Management**\n\n**New API Methods:**\n- `commitSync()`: Synchronously commits current position for all assigned partitions\n- `commitSync(Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndMetadata> offsets)`: Explicitly commit specific offsets per partition\n- `commitSync(Map, Duration timeout)`: With timeout specification\n- `commitAsync()`: Asynchronously commit with optional callback\n- `commitAsync(OffsetCommitCallback callback)`: With callback for success/failure\n- `commitAsync(Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndMetadata> offsets, OffsetCommitCallback callback)`: Async explicit offsets\n\n**Processing:** Handled by `CommitRequestManager` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CommitRequestManager.java) which:\n- Manages pending offset commit requests\n- Handles auto-commits based on `enable.auto.commit` and `auto.commit.interval.ms` configs\n- Supports both synchronous and asynchronous commit models\n- Provides callback invocation via `OffsetCommitCallbackInvoker`\n- Handles failures with `CommitFailedException` and `RetriableCommitFailedException`\n- Tracks member epoch for group coordination\n\n### 4. **Offset Fetching and Position Reset**\n\n**New API:**\n- `OffsetFetcher` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/OffsetFetcher.java):\n  - Fetches offsets for a given set of TopicPartition pairs\n  - Handles offset reset strategies via `resetOffsets()`\n  - Supports `offsetsForTimes()` to find offsets by timestamp\n  - Manages leader epoch information for offset validation\n  - Handles log truncation detection\n\n- `seek()` Methods:\n  - `seek(TopicPartition partition, long offset)`: Seek to specific offset\n  - `seek(TopicPartition partition, OffsetAndMetadata offsetAndMetadata)`: Seek with metadata\n\n### 5. **Committed Offset Retrieval**\n\n**New API:**\n- `committed(Set<TopicPartition> partitions)`: Get last committed offset for partitions\n- `committed(Set<TopicPartition> partitions, Duration timeout)`: With timeout\n- Returns `Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndMetadata>` for requested partitions\n\n### 6. **Position Query**\n\n**New API:**\n- `position(TopicPartition partition)`: Returns long offset of next record to be returned\n- `position(TopicPartition partition, Duration timeout)`: With timeout\n\n## Integration Examples\n\n### Camel Kafka Integration\n\nApache Camel (components/camel-kafka/src/main/java/org/apache/camel/component/kafka/) demonstrates the new API usage:\n\n1. **Factory Usage** (DefaultKafkaClientFactory.java):\n   - Creates instances of `org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.KafkaConsumer` directly\n   - Passes configuration properties to the constructor\n\n2. **Offset Tracking** (KafkaFetchRecords.java, line 468-469):\n   - Calls `consumer.committed(this.consumer.assignment())` to retrieve committed offsets\n   - Iterates through TopicPartition->OffsetAndMetadata mappings\n   - Uses `OffsetAndMetadata` objects for offset state\n\n## Key Behavioral Differences: Old vs New API\n\n### Automatic vs Manual Control\n\n**Legacy ConsumerConnector (Removed):**\n- Provided implicit offset management\n- Partitions were often managed automatically\n- Limited control over commit timing\n\n**New KafkaConsumer API:**\n- Explicit offset management via `commitSync()` and `commitAsync()`\n- Clear separation between position (current offset) and committed (stored) offset\n- Fine-grained control via `OffsetAndMetadata` including metadata and leader epoch\n- Support for both automatic (`enable.auto.commit`) and manual commit modes\n\n### Error Handling\n\n**New API:**\n- `CommitFailedException`: Thrown from `commitSync()` when commit fails non-retriably\n- `RetriableCommitFailedException`: For transient failures allowing retry\n- `NoOffsetForPartitionException`: When no offset reset strategy is configured\n- Clear exception hierarchy for different failure scenarios\n\n### Metrics and Monitoring\n\n**New API:**\n- `KafkaConsumerMetrics` (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/metrics/KafkaConsumerMetrics.java)\n- Provides detailed metrics for:\n  - Consumer lag\n  - Fetch rates and latencies\n  - Commit success/failure rates\n  - Rebalance timing and frequency\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe migration from the legacy ConsumerConnector to the modern KafkaConsumer API represents a shift toward:\n1. **Explicit offset management** using `OffsetAndMetadata` objects with metadata support\n2. **Clear position semantics** distinguishing between current position and committed offset\n3. **Flexible commit strategies** supporting both sync and async with callbacks\n4. **Better error handling** with specific exception types for different failure modes\n5. **Improved observability** through comprehensive metrics and leader epoch tracking\n6. **Modern protocol support** with both legacy and new consumer group protocols available via delegation\n\nDownstream projects like Apache Camel have successfully migrated to use the new `KafkaConsumer` API, leveraging its explicit offset management and improved control mechanisms."
}

