200→ * Setting {@code enable.auto.commit} means that offsets are committed automatically with a frequency controlled by
   201→ * the config {@code auto.commit.interval.ms}.
   202→ * <p>
   203→ * In this example the consumer is subscribing to the topics <i>foo</i> and <i>bar</i> as part of a group of consumers
   204→ * called <i>test</i> as configured with {@code group.id}.
   205→ * <p>
   206→ * The deserializer settings specify how to turn bytes into objects. For example, by specifying string deserializers, we
   207→ * are saying that our record's key and value will just be simple strings.
   208→ *
   209→ * <h4>Manual Offset Control</h4>
   210→ *
   211→ * Instead of relying on the consumer to periodically commit consumed offsets, users can also control when records
   212→ * should be considered as consumed and hence commit their offsets. This is useful when the consumption of the messages
   213→ * is coupled with some processing logic and hence a message should not be considered as consumed until it is completed processing.
   214→
   215→ * <p>
   216→ * <pre>
   217→ *     Properties props = new Properties();
   218→ *     props.setProperty(&quot;bootstrap.servers&quot;, &quot;localhost:9092&quot;);
   219→ *     props.setProperty(&quot;group.id&quot;, &quot;test&quot;);
   220→ *     props.setProperty(&quot;enable.auto.commit&quot;, &quot;false&quot;);
   221→ *     props.setProperty(&quot;key.deserializer&quot;, &quot;org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringDeserializer&quot;);
